    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4002478957" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4002478957" />
    <a title="Warren Fournier" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56665940-warren-fournier"><img alt="Warren Fournier" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641573555p2/56665940.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4002478957?book_show_action=true">Aug 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Warren Fournier" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Warren Fournier" href="/user/show/56665940-warren-fournier">Warren Fournier</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8149392-island-beneath-the-sea">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4002478957" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6714512536300698193">I was originally drawn to this title because of my own family&apos;s Haitian history, and was curious as to Chilean author Isabel Allende&apos;s take on the historical events that led my lineage across the sea to New Orleans for an American rebirth. Zarité, nicknamed Tété, is the main character of this splendid novel, and she takes the very same journey as my ancestors during the very same period in history. This is her tale of that journey over several decades.<br/><br/>Starting off as a young girl and a slave who</span>
  <span id="freeText6714512536300698193" style="display:none">I was originally drawn to this title because of my own family's Haitian history, and was curious as to Chilean author Isabel Allende's take on the historical events that led my lineage across the sea to New Orleans for an American rebirth. Zarité, nicknamed Tété, is the main character of this splendid novel, and she takes the very same journey as my ancestors during the very same period in history. This is her tale of that journey over several decades.<br /><br />Starting off as a young girl and a slave who dreams of freedom and thus is constantly running away, she comes to settle as the head housekeeper and nursemaid to wealthy white sugar cane producer Valmorain on the island of Saint-Domingue. And she also becomes his consort. She proves to be a stable emotional comfort to Valmorain's son and even his wife who languishes away in bed suffering from severe depression and psychotic panic. In every sense of the word, she is more of a wife than Valmorain ever had, so that his son refers to her with the forbidden word of "Maman." She also bears two of his own children. But rather than come to terms with the truth that his slaves are human beings, Valmorain persists on maintaining decorum by keeping her at a distance until his lust surfaces in the late hours. He refuses to release her from her bondage while he also resents his dependence on her. Neither is the heart of Tété with her maître, but rather with her loas, the beat of the talking drums, and freedom for her children. But revolution is in the air of Saint-Domingue, and the birth of a new nation is nigh. Will this be an opportunity for her to win her freedom? Or will she be a casualty of the revolution, rejected and shunned by both the blacks and whites at war?<br /><br />This is a truly remarkable tale of an innocent soul who struggles to maintain her dignity, virtue, identity, and her life despite all the raging forces of chaos and evil around her. Tété's story will inspire you and make you feel like you got something stuck in your eye. The narrative switches back and forth from the first-person perspective of Tété to the omniscient narrator, which I find rather effective in this case. The third-person voice is somewhat cold and distant, giving dry details of the historical drama unfolding in the background while expounding on the personal drama simultaneously going on in Tété's world. But when we switch to Tété's interpretation of those same events, as well as the consequences of those events on her fate, we are granted a much broader insight into this history despite reading about it from Tété's limited understanding.<br /><br />I particularly love the psychology behind how Tété comes to embrace the Catholic influence of her community with the ancient beliefs of her African ancestry, thus providing the reader with the entire history of voodoo from the perspective of one character. Also poignant was how, through her humble eyes, she sees the weakness behind the tyranny of slavery--any society that resorts to slave labor of their fellow brothers and sisters is doomed to fail, because it relies on the labor of those who gain nothing from their efforts. Those in slavery work at the minimum required to survive, and their work breeds contempt. Eventually, when the industry of a society is slave-dependent, then the slaves become the masters, because they have the power over the survival of the elite. Thus, this book is not only an indictment of slavery as a historical institution, but as a modern concept that exists to this day as any system that does not promote free enterprise, including communism. The author herself was separated from her family while in Venezuelan exile, so these themes are very close to her heart.<br /><br />There are so many rich characters in this novel, all with their virtues and their foibles, as well as delicious descriptive prose that really brings alive the historic settings as though the reader was truly and vividly remembering experiences from a previous life. For example, there is a wonderful scene that takes place in a bayou market run by Jean Lafitte and his pirates, and you can almost smell the swamp and the blacksmith smoke, hear the tinkle of the oars of pirogues through still water and the barking of corsair merchants as they heckle perspective customers, and taste the black rum and crimson seasoned crawfish.<br /><br />My only complaint is that somehow the book managed to outstay it's welcome. It seemed just a little too long. You may have a different experience and never want it to end. But for me, I did find the narrative to meander across familiar territory one too many times so that it tended to drag a bit at the end. Also, the passage of time did not seem very even. It seemed we were reading about the mundane of a particular selection of years for a good bulk of the book, and then without warning or transition, a decade has passed, which can be disorienting. There were times where I wanted more to happen, and it just wasn't to be, which tempted me to boredom. But overall, these were minor issues and your own mileage may vary.<br /><br />I think the vast majority of readers will enjoy this book, if not rank it as one of their favorites. Come and experience the Island for yourself. <br /><br />This is how it was.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6714512536300698193" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

